{"id":1066,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/items\/1066","public":true,"featured":false,"added":"2018-04-03T16:06:33+00:00","modified":"2019-08-21T17:57:38+00:00","item_type":null,"collection":{"id":17,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/collections\/17","resource":"collections"},"owner":{"id":1,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/users\/1","resource":"users"},"files":{"count":22,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/files?item=1066","resource":"files"},"tags":[],"element_texts":[{"html":false,"text":"George Catlin letters, 1827-1870","element_set":{"id":1,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/element_sets\/1","name":"Dublin Core","resource":"element_sets"},"element":{"id":50,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/elements\/50","name":"Title","resource":"elements"}},{"html":false,"text":"14","element_set":{"id":4,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/element_sets\/4","name":"Scripto","resource":"element_sets"},"element":{"id":54,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/elements\/54","name":"Percent Needs Review","resource":"elements"}},{"html":false,"text":"014086","element_set":{"id":4,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/element_sets\/4","name":"Scripto","resource":"element_sets"},"element":{"id":56,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/elements\/56","name":"Weight","resource":"elements"}},{"html":true,"text":"Four letters (1827-1870) written by George Catlin regarding his works and U.S. Indian policy. Catlin accepts a commission (1827) from William L. Stone, who later (1830-1839) published Catlin\u2019s \"Notes of eight years travel amongst the North American Indians\" in his New York Commercial Advertiser. Responding to Benjamin Silliman (1841), Catlin defends his conclusions regarding the pipe stone quarry and forwards a copy of his new \"Letters and notes on the manners ... of the North American Indians,\" which contained his observations on the subject. Catlin also offers (1844?) to sell his \"Album,\" presumably \"Catlin\u2019s North American Indian portfolio,\" for the reduced price of thirty pounds. Writing many years later to a Professor Harper, Catlin condemns the Jan., 1870, Piegan or Marias Massacre and the Indian policy of the U.S. military as revealed in a Mar., 1870, letter of Gen. P.H. Sheridan.\u00a0<a href=\"https:\/\/webvoyage.carli.illinois.edu\/nby\/cgi-bin\/Pwebrecon.cgi?DB=local&amp;v1=1&amp;BBRecID=136396\">View catalog record<\/a>","element_set":{"id":1,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/element_sets\/1","name":"Dublin Core","resource":"element_sets"},"element":{"id":41,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/elements\/41","name":"Description","resource":"elements"}},{"html":false,"text":"To transcribe","element_set":{"id":4,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/element_sets\/4","name":"Scripto","resource":"element_sets"},"element":{"id":53,"url":"http:\/\/publications.newberry.org\/transcription\/mms-transcribe\/api\/elements\/53","name":"Status","resource":"elements"}}],"extended_resources":[]}